free_txt: The Texas Variable Energy Cyclotron.
*By authors*.We have estimated tritium decay either
by using the known 3-H cross section in Al or by
assuming equal cross sections for 3-H and 3-He when no
cross section were available. In most cases the
estimated amount of 3-He via 3-H decay, calculated by
either method, was less than 5% of the total, and in
all cases it was well within experimental errors of
3-He measurements.
A 3-inch.*3-inch. Na-I(TL) crystal.
Large errors occurred when corrections for
total background gas or Na-22 decay were relatively
large. This was usually the case for foils irradiated
with protons near the threshold energy.
Total error. The main sources are:
Errors in target thickness are -+3%.
Errors in radioactive products were +-10%.
The error propagation yielded a total
error in the number of stable atoms which in most
cases was well below +-10%.
errors due to proton straggling
The Texas Variable Energy Cyclotron.
Si, Ca, Ti, Fe data (All data
renormalized in J.Geophys.Res. 81(1976)5689)
Stacks of thin Mg,Al,Si,Ca,Ca-F(2),Ti and stainless
and sum of Si,Cu,Mo,C,P and S up to 2.2%- foils were
bombarded in 12 irradiations.
The stacks consisted in each case of at least two
different foil types.
/By authors/ The He cross sections reported here
represent the sum of 1/3 those for natural Ca and 2/3
those for F. Since the He cross sections for Ca or F
alone are not known, separation of the individual
yields is impossible at this time.

-By Authors- From the cross-section values of 51-Cr and
52-Mn in type 302 stainless steel we have deduced cross
sections for 51-Cr and 52-Mn in natural Cr. Significant
yields of 51-Cr in the target are expected only from Cr
-18-20 at.% and Fe -66-74 at.% because production from
Mn - 2 at.%, aprox. and Ni - 7.5-9.5 at.% involves very
complex reactions.
